                    ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

                    LIST
                        with [ ]


                        list2 = [1,2, 2, 2, 3, 4, 5]
                    class material example
                         # the dif between TUPLE and LIST is because LIST is mutable, and TUPLE is not mutable.
                         # in some cases we SHOULD not be able to change the initial data.

                    example

                        list1 = [1, 2, 3, 22, 4, "TojtechAcademy"]
                        print(list1[5])

                        list1.remove(22) # remove tool goes by the name from the list, if its ,, we write 22. or any other value
                        print(list1)
                        list1.remove("TojtechAcademy")
                        print(list1)                       # will print the list without the "TojtechAcademy"

                        list1.insert(2, 10)                # insert goes by the position nr in the list. it will be inserted after the nr we tell.
                        print(list1)
                        list1.insert(0,77)                 # number 0 is calculated as a starting number point on the list.

                        list1.append("QA2 2022")           # append adds only a new value at the end of our list, always.
                        print(list1)

                    ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

                    TUPLE
                            with ( )

                        Tuple are immutable, they can not be changed or modified. only iteration
                        Tuple allows dublications.
                        Tuples are used to store multiple items in a single variable.
                        Tuple is one of 4 built-in data types in Python used to store collections of data, the other 3 are List, Set, and Dictionary, all with different qualities and usage.
                        A tuple is a collection which is ordered and unchangeable.
                        Tuple is a collection of values separated by comma and enclosed in parenthesis.
                        Unlike lists, tuples are immutable. The immutability can be considered as the identifying feature of tuples.

                    example

                        tuple1 = (1, 2, 4.6, "string")
                        print(tuple1[3])        # indexing will count from 0 as a starting point
                        print(tuple1)           #tuple # tuple are imutable, they can not be changed or modified. only iteration
                        print(type(tuple1))

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

        DICTIONARY or dict

        explaining what is dictionary -  create a variable = open the curly brackets,
            your variable name can be anything.
            data type to store multiple objects
            dictionary has ,,key,, that will hold a particular value asigned to it.

        example
            dictionary =  {"firstname": "Naseem", "Lastname": "Khalimov", 1: 6}
            print(dictionary)

            dictionary["firstname"] = "Naim"       # override data from dictionary for a string value
            print(dictionary["firstname"])
            dictionary[1] = 4                      # override data from dictionary for numeric value



